&gt;Hey Chad, what do you mean by &quot;how many arcs it falls into?&quot; My 
&gt;understanding is that any object will in general only fall into one 
&gt;arc. 

An object might fill more of the field of view than one arc. In order to
allow 
the network to search for a hiding strategy, the environment must let
the 
agents hide. So the rock they are hiding behind may take 5 degrees of
the 
field of view, and the agent might take 8 degrees of the field of view.
Hiding 
behind that rock would prove ineffective to perceptive agent in pursuit
. 
The environment to me is just as important as the multi agent 
aspect. A single agent can use features of the environment to position
itself 
more optimally with regard to the other agents. 
I&#39;m particularly interested in the hiding strategy, because I think it
requires 
both a visual type of perception, and some form of memory to remember 
a) that it is hiding, and 
b) who it is hiding from. 

The general gist is to randomize the environment during the search, much
like the random objects being thrown at the agent in the new version of 
Virtual Humans. 

&gt;That said, it is common practice in such &quot;radar&quot;-like sensor systems 
&gt;to have the arcs slightly overlap so you don&#39;t get jumpy transitions 
&gt;when an object moves from one arc to the other. 

I think using a narrow array of ray intercepts, and averaging the
results of 
small clusters into each input would give me a rough vision system. I
think 
that combined with the 360 degree radar-like sensor would provide a
peripheral 
vs foveal input bouquet. 

Why arn&#39;t simple vision systems a common practice? Is it only because it
takes longer to compute, or is there something else?

chad 

